        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Copywriting</strong> is the discipline of writing persuasive text designed to motivate readers to take a specific action — purchase, subscribe, click, call, or request a demo. It differs from content writing, which educates and builds trust gradually. Copy is measured on <strong>immediate conversion</strong>: did the reader do the next thing?</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Headline read rate</div>
            <div class="tms-value">8 in 10 readers</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Content</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Core frameworks</div>
            <div class="tms-value">AIDA · PAS · 4Cs</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Products are easy to copy. Communication styles are not. Copy is where a commodity becomes a brand — and where a landing page turns 3% of visitors into customers instead of 0.8%.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is copywriting?</h2>
        <p>Copywriting is persuasive writing engineered for one specific outcome. Every sentence exists to move the reader one step closer to an action: click the button, add to cart, book a call, reply to the email. When the copy fails, the traffic is wasted; when it works, it compounds every ad dollar and every SEO position behind it.</p>
        <p>The discipline dates back to the direct-mail era of David Ogilvy and Claude Hopkins, but the fundamentals haven't changed. What has changed is the surface area: the same copywriter now writes homepage headlines, Google Ads, email subject lines, TikTok hooks, push notifications, and CTA buttons — often within the same day.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The headline law</div>
          <p>Direct-response research is unusually consistent on one number: roughly <strong>8 out of 10 people read the headline</strong>, but only 2 out of 10 read past it. That means the headline alone controls 80% of the outcome. A good copywriter spends more editing time on the headline than on the entire body.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why copywriting matters</h2>
        <p>Copy touches revenue more directly than almost any other marketing lever. Five reasons it compounds:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Direct revenue impact.</strong> Better headlines, CTAs, and product descriptions lift <a href="/glossary/conversion-rate/">conversion rates</a> — the same traffic converts more.</li>
          <li><strong>Ad efficiency.</strong> A stronger ad hook increases CTR, which lifts <a href="/glossary/quality-score/">Quality Score</a>, which lowers <a href="/glossary/cost-per-click/">CPC</a>. One good headline can cut ad costs 20-40%.</li>
          <li><strong>Brand differentiation.</strong> Products are easily copied. A distinctive voice is not. Copy is where a commodity brand escapes the price war.</li>
          <li><strong>Scale across channels.</strong> The same copy skill powers emails, ads, product descriptions, sales decks, and onboarding flows. It scales farther than any single marketing tactic.</li>
          <li><strong>Compounding traffic value.</strong> Turning visitors into customers means every future SEO gain, referral, and paid-media dollar is worth more.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How copywriting works</h2>
        <p>Great copy follows a three-step method: research, structure, then edit ruthlessly.</p>
        <h3>Start with empathy</h3>
        <p>Read customer support tickets, sales-call recordings, and reviews. Copywriters steal exact customer language and echo it back — because the customer already believes it. If a buyer says "I couldn't find anything my kid would actually eat," that becomes the headline.</p>
        <h3>Apply a proven framework</h3>
        <p>Frameworks aren't rules; they're scaffolds that prevent staring at a blank page. Two frameworks dominate:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>PAS — Problem, Agitate, Solve.</strong> Best for ads, emails, and short landing sections.</li>
          <li><strong>AIDA — Attention, Interest, Desire, Action.</strong> Best for long-form sales pages and product launches.</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Edit ruthlessly</h3>
        <p>First drafts are always too long. Cut adverbs, cut hedging language, cut anything that doesn't move the reader forward. Prefer active voice, short sentences, specific numbers. Read every draft out loud — if you stumble, the reader will too.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of copywriting</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Where it lives</th><th>Primary goal</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Direct-response</strong></td><td>Landing pages, sales pages, ads</td><td>Immediate purchase or signup</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>SEO copywriting</strong></td><td>Blog posts, category pages</td><td>Rank + convert search traffic</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Email copywriting</strong></td><td>Newsletters, drip sequences</td><td>Opens, clicks, replies</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Brand copywriting</strong></td><td>Homepage, About, product pages</td><td>Identity + positioning</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Ad copywriting</strong></td><td>Google Ads, Meta Ads, LinkedIn</td><td>CTR at the lowest CPC</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>UX / microcopy</strong></td><td>Button labels, error states, onboarding</td><td>Clarity + friction removal</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real copywriting examples</h2>
        <h3>1. SaaS headline swap — 34% more demos</h3>
        <p>A project management SaaS changed its hero from <em>"Project Management Software"</em> to <em>"Stop losing projects in your inbox."</em> Same product, same traffic, same page structure. Demo requests jumped 34% in the first month — because the new headline named a specific pain the visitor already felt.</p>
        <h3>2. Gym email subject line — 42% lift</h3>
        <p>A gym A/B tested two subject lines. Version A: <em>"Try our new class schedule."</em> Version B: <em>"Your gym is 4 minutes from your office."</em> Version B won by 42% opens. Specificity beats novelty, every time.</p>
        <h3>3. Ecommerce product page — from feature list to outcome</h3>
        <p>A DTC brand replaced <em>"Made from 100% merino wool, machine washable"</em> with <em>"The sweater you'll actually wear on the plane, in the meeting, and to dinner."</em> Add-to-cart rate rose 21%. Features tell; outcomes sell.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Copywriting vs content writing — which do you need?</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Copywriting</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Goal: an immediate action</li>
              <li>Measured on conversion rate</li>
              <li>Short-form, high-density language</li>
              <li>Lives on landing pages, ads, emails, CTAs</li>
              <li>Example: a pricing page that turns 4% of visitors into trials</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4><a href="/glossary/content-marketing/">Content writing</a></h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Goal: build trust and educate over time</li>
              <li>Measured on rankings, time on page, return visits</li>
              <li>Long-form, informational</li>
              <li>Lives on blog posts, guides, glossaries</li>
              <li>Example: a 2,500-word guide that ranks for a category term</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>You need both. Content writing brings visitors in. Copywriting decides what percentage of them stay.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 copywriting best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Write the headline last.</strong> Draft the body first, then find the single strongest promise inside it and lift it up.</li>
          <li><strong>Steal customer language verbatim.</strong> If a reviewer said it, you can too. It disarms skepticism instantly.</li>
          <li><strong>One idea per sentence.</strong> Every AND that could be a period, make a period.</li>
          <li><strong>Lead with the benefit, then the feature.</strong> Not "10,000mAh battery" — "seven full days without a charger."</li>
          <li><strong>Use specific numbers.</strong> "Doubles your revenue" is weak. "Cut CPA from $380 to $210" is unfair.</li>
          <li><strong>Match the CTA to the buying stage.</strong> Cold visitors don't buy. Ask them to read, watch, or download first.</li>
          <li><strong>A/B test the headline before anything else.</strong> Test button copy last. Headlines swing outcomes 5-10x further.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — writing to impress, not to sell</div>
          <p>The moment copy sounds "clever," you've lost. Clever copy makes the reader admire the writer; useful copy makes the reader take action. If a customer would not use the phrase, cut it.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common copywriting mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Feature dumping.</strong> Listing specs without translating them into outcomes.</li>
          <li><strong>Multiple CTAs on one page.</strong> One page, one primary action.</li>
          <li><strong>Passive voice.</strong> "Mistakes were made" ≠ "We made mistakes." Own the sentence.</li>
          <li><strong>Vague promises.</strong> "Best-in-class," "world-class," "cutting-edge" — cut all of them.</li>
          <li><strong>No proof.</strong> Every claim needs a number, screenshot, testimonial, or logo behind it.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps</h2>
        <p>Our editorial team writes conversion-driven copy for the pages that decide whether SEO traffic actually converts — homepages, category pages, landing pages, and CTA blocks. We pair copywriting with the underlying <a href="/glossary/keyword-research/">keyword research</a>, so the language matches what buyers actually type into Google, and then rewrite until the page earns its rankings twice: once from Google, once from the reader.</p>

